GSEM factor analysis - sensitivity analyses

AA & JP

12 July, 2024

Genomic SEM factor analysis: sensitivity follow-up analyses

We take the model that showed the best fit and carry it forward to do sensitivity and robustness analyses. I used the EFA-based 4-factor model, the bifactor (or S-1) per substance, and bifactor (or S-1) per trait type.

Odd versus even chromosomes

4-factor model

I used the whole genome to fit both EFA and CFA models for practical and theoretical reasons. If it is true that for many traits the genetic signal is rather localized (rather than spread out evenly across the genome) this would give a different factor structure in different chromosome subsets. To check this, I compare the factor structure for even and odd chromosomes separately. Indeed, the factor structure is quite different.

EFA for even:

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.EVEN.RData')

Ssmooth <- as.matrix((nearPD(ldscOut$S, corr = FALSE))$mat)

EFA <-factanal(covmat = Ssmooth, factors = 4, rotation = 'promax')
print(EFA$loadings, digits = 2, cutoff = .3, sort = TRUE)

Bifactor per substance model

In addition, we have a look if the best-fitting model replicates in even and odd chromosomes separately. The fit is poorer than in the total genome, again suggesting the influence of localised signals.

In even chromosomes:

load("data/mldsc_29May2023.14.EVEN.RData")

bif <- 'G =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP

ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP 
DRG =~ NA*COCDEP + OPIODEP

G ~~ 0*ALC + 0*CAN + 0*DRG

G~~1*G
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN
DRG~~1*DRG

a>.001
CANEV~~a*CANEV

b>.001
OPIODEP~~b*OPIODEP
'

#run the model
fit <- usermodel(ldscOut, estimation = "DWLS", model = bif, CFIcalc = TRUE)
fitlabel <- paste0("CFI = ", round(fit$modelfit$CFI,3), ", SRMR = ", round(fit$modelfit$SRMR,3))
kable(fitlabel)

Orthogonal 4-factor model

To check, we tried a varimax rotation on the 4-factor EFA. The solution suggested by the EFA is not too different. Fitting this model in CFA while forcing the factors to be orthogonal (uncorrelated) gives a rather high SRMR, though CFI is excellent. The factor solution seems a bit less intuitive, and the path estimates are very wild.

EFA:

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.TOT.RData')

Ssmooth <- as.matrix((nearPD(ldscOut$S, corr = FALSE))$mat)

EFA <-factanal(covmat = Ssmooth, factors = 4, rotation = 'varimax')
print(EFA$loadings, digits = 2, cutoff = .3, sort = TRUE)

CFA:

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.TOT.RData')

CFA <- '
F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + SMKAGE + COCDEP + ALCFRQ + SMKINI
F2 =~ NA*SMKAGE + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + CANEV + SMKINI
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP
F4 =~ NA*CANDEP + CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

F1~~1*F1
F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3
F4~~1*F4

F1~~0*F2 + F3 + F4
F2~~0*F3 + F4
F3~~0*F4

a > .001
 SMKINI ~~ a*SMKINI
  
b>.001
ALCFRQ ~~ b*ALCFRQ
'

#run the model
fit <- usermodel(ldscOut, estimation = "DWLS", model = CFA, CFIcalc = TRUE)
fitlabel <- paste0("CFI = ", round(fit$modelfit$CFI,3), ", SRMR = ", round(fit$modelfit$SRMR,3))

Plot

semPlotModel_GSEM=function(gsem.object=GWISoutput , est.label="STD_All"){ 
      
       object=gsem.object$results
       object$free=0
       numb=1:length(which(object$op!="~~"))
       object$free[which(object$op!="~~")]=numb
       varNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "ov")
       factNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "lv")
       factNames <- factNames[!factNames %in% varNames]
       n <- length(varNames)
       k <- length(factNames)
       if (is.null(object$label)) 
         object$label <- rep("", nrow(object))
       semModel <- new("semPlotModel")
       object$est <- object[,est.label]
       object$se <- object[,"STD_Genotype_SE"]
       
       if (is.null(object$group)) 
         object$group <- ""
       semModel@Pars <- data.frame(label = object$label, lhs = ifelse(object$op == 
                                                                        "~" | object$op == "~1", object$rhs, object$lhs), edge = "--", 
                                   rhs = ifelse(object$op == "~" | object$op == "~1", object$lhs, 
                                                object$rhs), est = object$est, std = NA, group = object$group, 
                                   fixed = object$free==0, par = object$free, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~*~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~"] <- "~>"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "=~"] <- "->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~1"] <- "int"
       semModel@Pars$edge[grepl("\\|", object$op)] <- "|"
       semModel@Thresholds <- semModel@Pars[grepl("\\|", semModel@Pars$edge), 
                                            -(3:4)]
       semModel@Pars <- semModel@Pars[!object$op %in% c(":=", "<", 
                                                        ">", "==", "|", "<", ">"), ]
       semModel@Vars <- data.frame(name = c(varNames, factNames), 
                                   manifest = c(varNames, factNames) %in% varNames, exogenous = NA, 
                                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@ObsCovs <- list()
       semModel@ImpCovs <- list()
       semModel@Computed <- FALSE
       semModel@Original <- list(object)
       return(semModel)
       
}

bif <- 'G =~ NA*F1 + F2 + F3 + F4

F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + ALCFRQ + SMKINI + COCDEP
F2 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP
F3 =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI + SMKAGE
F4 =~ NA*CANDEP + OPIODEP + COCDEP

F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3

Index event bias-adjusted - bifactor - per substance model

We now re-fit the best theoretical model (bifactor per-substance) using Hunter-slope adjusted summary statistics for smoking and cannabis traits. Interestingly, the SMK and CAN factors now have a correlation >1, and the bifactor model does not converge (restricting to 1 does not work).

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.hunted.age.14.TOT.RData')

CFA <- 'G =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP

ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP

G~~1*G
SMK~~1*SMK
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN
DRG~~1*DRG

a>.001
 CANEV~~a*CANEV

b>.001
  OPIODEP ~~ b*OPIODEP

c>-0.99
  SMK~~c*CAN

HDL

Standard 4-factor EFA

In addition, we explore the factor structure in the HDL-based covariance matrix. Note that opioid dependence is excluded (because its variance couldn’t be estimated with HDL), which will account for some of the difference in the factor structure.

EFA:

load("data/hdl_10January2024.14.RData")

Ssmooth <- as.matrix((nearPD(hdlOut$S, corr = FALSE))$mat)

EFA <-factanal(covmat = Ssmooth, factors = 4, rotation = 'promax')
print(EFA, digits = 2, cutoff = .3, sort = TRUE)

Theoretical bifactor - per substance model

Now we repeat the model that fit the data best (bifactor - per substance) with an HDL-based covariance structure (instead of LDSC). The covariance of opioid dependence could not be estimated and is not included in these models. Therefore, there is no DRG factor and COCDEP is included only in the general G factor. As with the bias-adjusted model, the correlation between SMK and CAN has to be restricted <.99. The fit of the S-1 model without the SMK factor is rather terrible, and CANDEP does not load on the cannabis factor.

load("data/hdl_10January2024.14.RData")

bif <- 'G =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP + COCDEP

SMK =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI 
ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP 

G ~~ 0*SMK + 0*ALC + 0*CAN

G~~1*G
SMK~~1*SMK
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN

a>.001
   ALCP~~a*ALCP
  
b>.001  
  CANEV~~b*CANEV
  
c>-.99
  CAN~~c*SMK
'

fit <- usermodel(hdlOut, estimation = "DWLS", model = bif, CFIcalc = TRUE)
